post_text:
The West Branch Community School District is looking for substitute teachers! We have flexible opportunities for those with limited availability. Help us ensure a bright and successful school year for our students and families.

Substitute teachers must have a valid Iowa Department of Education teaching license or a substitute license (or a substitute authorization if you do not hold a teaching certification).

All candidates will undergo an interview and must pass a background check. If you're already certified, apply today: https://www.west-branch.k12.ia.us/human-resources/

If you're seeking certification, you can take a class through Grant Wood AEA. Learn more here: https://tinyurl.com/yyznwdqv.

Once you've taken the course, you must apply for a license through the Iowa Board of Educational Examiners: https://boee.iowa.gov/

We know many of you have questions about what teaching and learning will look like in the upcoming school year. We want to do our best to answer those questions.

The West Branch Community School District will soon have a Frequently Asked Questions link on our website. There, we will post answers to questions we have received from families. You may submit your questions here: https://bit.ly/WBCSDQuestions

Our goal is to have the FAQ up by August 10. We also look to provide further information on mitigation protocols, cohort groups A & B, schedule details and guidance from Cedar County Public Health and the Iowa Department of Public Health.

Please be on the lookout for this information soon! Thank you for your continued support, patience and understanding.

post_text:
Congratulations to Matt Cain, recipient of the STEM Innovator Award from the Iowa City Area Business Partnership! The award recognizes creativity and innovation in providing enhanced problem-based learning opportunities to students.

STEM (science, technology, engineering and math) has been a key focus in the West Branch CSD as we prepare students for the careers and postsecondary opportunities of the future.

We are incredibly proud of and grateful for Mr. Cain’s leadership in our STEM and robotics program. He has provided outstanding opportunities for our students when it comes to building 21st century skills. Please join us in congratulating him!

Learn more about the award: https://iowacityarea.com/2020-innovation-in-education-awards/

post_text:
Earlier today, Governor Reynolds announced that summer sports and activities may begin June 1.

After the announcement, the Iowa Department of Education provided school districts with guidance regarding the rules and restrictions that will apply to summer sports and activities. We are now reviewing that guidance and will communicate with our student-athletes and families once we have made some key decisions on next steps.

Above all else, the safety of our student-athletes is our top priority.

In the meantime, we want to thank everyone for their continued patience. We will follow up soon with more information.

post_text:
Today, Governor Reynolds announced that all Iowa schools will remain closed through the end of the school year to help manage the COVID-19 pandemic.

We know this decision has caused a great deal of concern and disappointment for our students, staff and families. When we were first directed to close our school buildings in March, we did not realize it would be the last time we would see our students in person this school year. Please know that we share in your disappointment.

We will continue with virtual learning until the last day for students. It is our hope that we will be able to reschedule prom and we will continue to look at various options for graduation, but we do not yet know how these events will look.

Thank you again for your patience, understanding and flexibility during this unprecedented time. We ask that you continue to check emails for updates. Please continue to stay safe, practice social distancing and remain at home as much as possible.

West Branch High School yearbook, The Growler, would like for its students to document their lives while out of school during the COVID-19 coronavirus outbreak. We would like for you to submit photos in order to help us chronicle this historic event.

For now, spring activities here at WBHS have been put on hold. The WBHS yearbook staff would like for students to send us your photos of activities that you are doing to get through this time. Such as; watching movies, exercising at home, completing the resources teachers have provided, taking care of siblings, playing with pets, doing chores, hobbies, etc.

Again, we would really like your input, this is an historic event in all of our lives. Your participation is greatly appreciated. Students may send their photos to Mrs. Hasenbank at LHasenbank@west-branch.k12.ia.us.

post_text:
#teacherlife

What do our staff and teachers do during the summer?

4th grade teacher, Mr. Shultice, got the chance to do a bit of field research with his family at Olympic National Park. Doesn’t it look amazing?

Mr. Shultice and the 4th grade teaching team do a large project based learning unit on national parks every spring. The students select a park and then research it (Social Studies) and write its rangers (English). They also pull in science & math components and then finally put together a display board that they present to parents and community members during the National Park Fair. As a culmination of the project, all students receive a pass for free entrance into national parks for them and their family.

Our teachers are passionate about what they teach & their learning never ends!

#teacherlife

What do our staff and teachers do during the summer?

They love to learn as much as they love to teach! Mrs. Seydel, 2nd grade teacher at Hoover Elementary, spent a couple of days at an amazing training, ‘The Study of and Classroom Strategies for Dyslexia.’

West Branch Community School District’s Vision is: A Future Focused Community of Learners. We’re so thankful that Mrs. Seydel & all of our teachers take this to heart and continue their learning so that they are prepared to serve ALL students!

Cedar County Residents:

Community Action of Eastern Iowa is taking applications for free school supplies until July 18, 2019. Eligible households will receive school supplies for their children attending kindergarten through 12th grade this fall.

Call 563-886-3191 or 800-920-3191 on Tuesday or Thursday. Call or text 563-549-9375 on Monday, Wednesday or Friday.

Families are required to provide proof of household income, must reside in Cedar County and will asked to show TWO forms of address verification.

What do our staff and teachers do during the summer?

Mrs. Thompson, High School Ag Teacher, and her kids spend time hanging out in fields! This week she was supervising while recent graduate Ethan cut hay on the Thompson farm. It’s a joint project with the Park and the FFA students are currently growing and bailing hay on the property. The funds earned when it’s sold are put into the West Branch Foundation to use towards future endeavors on the Farm and in the classroom. Project-based learning in action!

A huge congrats to:
Alora and Frishy Freedom (aka Doc)
Sylvia and Divas Drive Diesels (aka Ollie)
Annie and Just Zip My Wranglers (aka Juliette)

Can’t wait to hear the stories behind those names!

post_text:
4th grader, Alexa, presented to a National Park Service employee during the National Park Fair today at Hoover Elementary.

The entire 4th grade picked a National Park, and then researched it in Social Studies, wrote two essays about it in Writing, created a scenic painting of it in Art, and learned about the animals and climate in the park during Science. Then students put together poster boards and presented to parents and community members. Just one small example of how our students are immersed in project based learning everyday!

post_text: When your school is in a town with a ton of history, you happen upon some really unique learning experiences. Thanks to Pete Swisher and the staff at Herbert Hoover National Historic Site for bringing this opportunity to our school! Check out the amazing Brooder house that students in our ACE program built!
shared_text:
Herbert Hoover National Historic Site
April 3, 2019 at 10:44 AM ·

Herbert Hoover National Historic Site would like to congratulate and thank the Architecture, Construction and Engineering (A.C.E.) program at West Branch High School for their recent completion of the Thompson Farm Brooder House. The students built a brooder house similar in design to the originally constructed building for our turn-of-the-century Iowa farmstead. The original Brooder house was prefabricated by Green Gable Builders out of Onawa, Iowa which began business in 1923 through the 1950's.
